            <article class="layout-article" id="firehose-21538756">
        <header class="story-header">
            
            <h1 id="title-21538756"><a href="//it-beta.slashdot.org/story/11/06/10/0741204/explaining-the-business-of-spam">Explaining The Business of Spam</a></h1>
            
                <h4>
                    
                    <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~timothy" class="author">timothy</a> posted  more than 3 years ago  | from the wading-through-the-muck-even-now dept. 
                    

                    
                </h4>
            
                <span class="topic" id="topic-21538756"> <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/index2.pl?fhfilter=spam" onclick="return addfhfilter('spam');">
            <img src="//c.fsdn.com/s/topics/spam_64.png" width="30px" height="30px" alt="Spam" title="Spam">
        </a></span>
                <a href="//it-beta.slashdot.org/story/11/06/10/0741204/explaining-the-business-of-spam"><span class="comment-count">74</span></a>
        </header>
	
            
        <div class="elips" data-link="//it-beta.slashdot.org/story/11/06/10/0741204/explaining-the-business-of-spam">
            <p  id="text-21538756">
                    
                        ATMAvatar writes <i>"The <a href="http://www.ieee-security.org/TC/SP2011/index.html">IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy</a> hosted in Oakland nearly three weeks ago featured a <a href="http://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2011/06/spam_as_a_busin.html">study on the economics of spam</a>.  It attempts to identify and analyze the chain of businesses behind spam and the products that are featured.  The goal was to take a more comprehensive look at the mechanics behind the industry in an attempt to identify better, alternative means to combat spam."</i>
                        
                    
            </p>
        </div>
        <footer class="article-footer">
            
        </footer>
	
    </article>
