        <article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_36402378" data-cid="36402378">
    <div id="comment_36402378">
        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re:Low costs..."><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re:Low costs...<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~WuphonsReach" class="author" title="author name and user ID">WuphonsReach (684551) </a> | more than 3 years ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=2227792&cid=36402378">(#36402378)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_36402378" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><i>I wonder... is the conversion rate dropping because people are smarter, or because the sheer amount of spam has risen?<br>
<br>
Yes, a bit from column A and probably a bit from column B.<br>
<br>
Plus, spam filters keep getting better and better, which makes it even harder for your spam to land in the respondent's mailbox.<br>
<br>
If, in 2001, you had to send out 100,000 spams, of which only 10,00 would land in someone's mailbox and only 500 (5%) of those would convert, you probably count that as a 200:1 ratio.<br>
<br>
Now, what if the spam filters block 99% of your messages?  Now, only 1,000 of your 100k spam blast is seen, and people are a bit smarter so only 3% click through.  You end up with only 30 suckers and have a ratio of 3333:1.<br>
<br></i></div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_36402378">
                <div class="comment-footer-controls btn-group btn-group-sm" data-sid="2227792" data-cid="36402378">
