            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Charging for E-mail?"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Charging for E-mail?<span> (2)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~bejiitas_wrath" class="author" title="author name and user ID">bejiitas_wrath (825021) </a> | more than 3 years ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=2227792&cid=36398374">(#36398374)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_36398374" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="2" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p><a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/blog/2006/feb/05/aolyahootost" title="guardian.co.uk" rel="nofollow">http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/blog/2006/feb/05/aolyahootost</a> <span class="domain-text"> [guardian.co.uk]</span> </p><p>What happened to the rumours a while ago about charging for E-mail? This might stem the tide if an E-Mail cost a very small fee to send, but considering the volumes of E-Mail sent around the world, this would not be very popular at all. There will be some bright spark out there that will come up with a solution for spam E-mails soon, but those Nigerian E-mails sure are funny...</p></div>
