<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_36398478" data-cid="36398478">
    <div id="comment_36398478">
        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re:Charging for E-mail?"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re:Charging for E-mail?<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~WrongSizeGlass" class="author" title="author name and user ID">WrongSizeGlass (838941) </a> | more than 3 years ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=2227792&cid=36398478">(#36398478)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_36398478" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body">It's kind of tough to charge back to these fake domains, shell companies and other institutions that are spread out over many countries (some of which actually don't care how their citizens or companies bring in income). If they need to pay for email in advance, well, who's going to put a gate keeper in place to check each and every email, verify they have an available balance, deduct the cost of the email and let the message through? We can't even verify the sender on most email. <br> <br>
Requiring every domain to use something similar to domain keys &amp; domain signatures would be a nice start, but those aren't free from problems or errors.</div>
