            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~yarnosh" class="author" title="author name and user ID">yarnosh (2055818) </a> | more than 3 years ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=2227792&cid=36401630">(#36401630)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_36401630" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>Or people could just start implementing the very good filtering solutions that are out there. I know it sounds like a bad idea to enter an arms race with spammers, but this is probably one of those rare cases where it has worked. We're winning. Filtering solutions are GOOD. Turns out the more things spammers do to try to slip through filters, the more obvious their attempts become and the easier they are to pick out.

</p><p>When was the last time you saw spam in your gmail account? I haven't seen a single instance in months except for a few messages coming through some poorly maintained mailing lists, from which I usually unsubscribe when I start getting spam.</p></div>
